<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-039-226 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 395 303</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Oct 7 1991 v8 n40 p27(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>User learns hard lesson about disaster recovery; PaineWebberestablishes plan for catastrophes. (fire, flood damage majornetwork nodes)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Molloy, Maureen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>PaineWebber Inc has learned to make disaster recovery planning atop priority after experiencing two major catastrophes in a shortperiod of time.andP;  A fire in the winter of 1990 gutted the firm'sPhiladelphia regional headquarters, and a water tower breakflooded a regional office in Boston some months later.andP;  Both siteswere key nodes on the company's nationwide T-1 backbone network,and both incidents severely disrupted network service.andP;  Managersat PaineWebber have since developed new backup systems andprocedures and implemented a formal disaster-recovery plan.andP;  Thecompany's computer operations department worked with ATandamp;T todevelop a handbook explaining the steps to take at each major nodeto redirect circuits if the node is disabled.andP;  Call reroutingplans exist for all sites and for the remote sites connected tothem.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   PaineWebber Inc. (Data processing).andO;Topic:     Disaster recoveryCase StudyManagement of EDPT1 CommunicationsBrokerage Industry.andO;Feature:   illustrationmap.andO;Caption:   PaineWebber's nationwide T-1 network. (map)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>